sample.title: We Went To Intel‚Äôs Arizona Chip Fab To See If It Can Regain Its Edge
sample.description:
Intel is now in high-volume production of its latest chip node, 18A, at a new fab in Arizona, where it hopes to compete with TSMC and bring advanced chip manufacturing back to U.S. soil. But so far, no major external customers are making on 18A. Following years of missteps and delays, Intel faces an uphill battle to regain foundry customer trust. In the meantime, its received billions from Nvidia, SoftBank and the U.S. government - which took a 10% stake in the struggling company. CNBC got the first ever on-camera tour inside Fab52 and asked its foundry head about why this time, it won‚Äôt fail.

sample.title: Waymo Leads The 2025 Robotaxi Surge As Zoox Expands And Tesla Races To Catch Up
sample.description:
Alphabet-owned Waymo scaled up and now leads the American robotaxi market by far, while Baidu-owned Apollo Go dominated in China. In the San Francisco Bay Area, there are now multiple robotaxi services operating, including Zoox and Waymo, although only Waymo provides commercial rides completely free of any human safety operators. Tesla finally launched their robotaxis in Austin and San Francisco but both states include human safety supervisors onboard ready to quickly take over driving. In December, Musk confirmed that driverless robotaxi tests had begun in Austin, which drove Tesla stock to a year high.

sample.title: Will China ever speak up for Ukraine? | BBC Ukrainecast
sample.description:
Ukrainian president Volodymyr Zelensky has warned that his army will struggle to fight on effectively if a crunch European summit ends without a solution to an imminent deficit in Kyiv's finances. 

Meanwhile, Vladimir Putin has referred to European leaders as "piglets" as he dismissed any peace deal which does not "unconditionally" satisfy Russia's pre-invasion aims. This week, Lucy is joined in the studio by the BBC‚Äôs chief international correspondent Lyse Doucet, security correspondent Frank Gardner, and Europe digital editor Paul Kirby, to answer your questions. Could a plan to redeploy frozen Russian assets crash Europe‚Äôs economy? Which competing visions are at play inside the White House as the US ramps up peace efforts? sample.title: Epstein files released - thousands of documents now on US Justice Dept website | BBC News
sample.description:
BREAKING NEWS:  Thousands of documents from two criminal investigations into the late sex offender Jeffrey Epstein have been released in the United States. ¬† 

Among the files are details of Epstein's contacts book, revealing new details of his association with wealthy and powerful people.

The first folder released on the Department of Justice website 
 contains photographs taken during an FBI search of Epstein's Manhattan home. One image shows black-gloved hands holding up a piece of paper with the address of what was Epstein's primary residence.

Among the files are many new photographs.  Some show the former US president Bill Clinton, apparently in a hot tub and also in a swimming pool.  Another shows Mr Clinton alongside Epstein.  The former president has never been accused of wrongdoing by survivors of Epstein‚Äôs abuse. 

Other photographs shows Epstein with Mick Jagger and the Microsoft boss Bill Gates.   Being named or pictured in the files is not an indication of wrongdoing. Many of those identified in other releases have denied any wrongdoing in relation to Epstein. 

There are new pictures of Ghislaine Maxwell, Epstein‚Äôs former partner and confidante, who is serving a 20-year jail sentence for sex trafficking.

Epstein was convicted of soliciting prostitution in 2008.   Later allegations were not brought  to trial, because he was found dead in his jail cell in New York in 2019.

The files were released on the day of a legal deadline for the Justice Department to make the information public.  However the US Deputy Attorney-General said not all the files are being released. 

Jane Hill presents BBC News at Ten reporting by Tom Bateman and Andrew Verity.
